subSubSection.paragraph:
Female macroptera.
With the structural characters of the genus. Body brown (
Fig. 4
); all femora brown, tibiae light brown, tarsi yellowish; antennal segments I brown, II brown with yellowish apex, III yellow, IV yellow but brownish distally, V–VIII brown but the base of V paler (
Fig. 6
). Fore wing mostly pale, with one dark band in basal second quarter, apex usually darker (
Fig. 11
).

Head length about 0.9 times basal width, with weak transverse sculpture in posterior part, usually with 1 to 3 tubercles in front of anterior ocellus. Ocellar setae III about 1.6 times as long as distance between posterior ocelli, and arising between posterior ocelli; postocular setae I–III rather apart from compound eyes (
Fig. 7
). Forked sense cone on segment III and IV usually not extending beyond basal third of next segment, segment VII basally wider, and usually shorter than VIII (
Fig. 6
).

Pronotum almost smooth, with two pairs of posteroangular setae, inner usually longer (
Fig. 8
). Metanotum striated laterally, anterior margin irregularly reticulate, posterior half nearly smooth; median setae close to anterior margin and close to each other, paired campaniform sensilla arising medially (
Fig. 9
). Fore wing first vein with 2 to 7 setae on basal half, 2 setae distally, usually without a median seta.

Male macroptera
. Similar to female but smaller (
Fig. 5
); abdominal sternites III–VII with narrowly elongated pore plates (
Fig. 15
) (on VII rarely reduced to small spots) (
Fig. 14
); tergites IX–X as 
Fig. 16
.

